You can use the union type | to represent multiple possible types for a variable. However, if you know that in practice a variable will only have one of those types, you can explicitly cast it using the as keyword followed by the desired type. This will tell the type system that you are certain the variable has that type, even though it is technically possible for it to have any of the types in the union.

For example:

function add(val: string | number): number {
  return val + 1; // Error: Operands of '+' cannot be applied to types 'string' and 'number'.

}

function add2(val: string | number): number {
  return (val as string) + 1; // OK, now 'val' is treated as a string
}

function add3(val: string | number): number {
  if (typeof val === 'string') {
    return val + 1;
  } else {
    return (val as number) + 1;
  }
}

